>>18145489
Not that anon, but I think you should put periods at the end of your sentences.

A your use of commas could also use some work. Some of them are unnecessary, or are in the wrong place.
For example:
>be it you confusing her for a guy, the similar tastes in videogames or just fucking about in PE, you two just bonded since primary and kept at it ever since
The second comma here is in the wrong place. It should be after 'videogames' instead of 'PE'.
Some sentences, like the one on line 32, also feel like they run on a bit too long. I think you're trying to describe to many things at once; it would be better to split them up into their own sentences so it is easier to read.

Aside from the commas, periods, and some grammar, everything else seems fine.
Keep writing! I need more tomboyish lynxes in my life.

Hi Anon, this is pretty darn good so far, especially for a first crack at this sort of thing. (I'm about to be walking out on the same thin ice, here, so I know the feeling).

The start is a little exposition-y, but it's not egregious. If you keep on truckin' from there, and delve into the meat of it - now that your main is up and on the move - it'll be fine.

If you want to polish your craft a bit, I'd try thinning out the reminiscing and spacing out your description of Anna. A perfect example of this would be working some of your description of her build / features into the background story about play wrestling. It'd give some context to how she's able to go toe to toe with your Anon, and save you having to toss up a character ref. sheet in paragraph #2.

Last but not least, let me scratch my grammar nazi itch. I understand that this is a quick pass, but it'd serve you well to have a quick reread and knock out the various minor spelling mistakes / incorrect word usage. None of it's egregious, but it does get a bit flow breaking for your reader. As to stylistic grammar errors written into your author's dialogue - they're fine but leave an opportunity to add depth to tone later. In this case, I'm referring to dropping sentence subjects, treating prepositions as sentences, etc. I'd personally recommend dialing it back a bit. Having more structured grammar when the author is speaking and changing into stream of consciousness when writing internal monologues or explicit speech helps to separate the two for your reader. It's also a useful tool for fleshing out your characters! Again, it's a style thing not a structure thing, but you're looking for feedback so... uh... there 'ya go!

I'm Glad to see a new writefag here, and I'm genuinely looking to see where you take this story!
